# Data License & Provenance — PhishRewrite

The **code** in this repository is released under the MIT License (see `LICENSE`).
This file governs the **data**: the upstream corpora consumed and the derived
benchmark redistributed by this project.

## Scope

PhishRewrite ingests three publicly released research email corpora and produces
a derived, processed benchmark (cleaned emails + LLM-generated rewrites used to
measure detector robustness). We redistribute **derived/processed** text and the
generated rewrites; we do not claim ownership of the underlying message content,
which remains with the original senders/maintainers.

## Upstream sources & terms

1. **SpamAssassin Public Corpus** — used: `easy_ham`, `easy_ham_2`, `hard_ham`
   (HAM ONLY; the `spam` / `spam_2` subsets are NOT used).
   Source: https://spamassassin.apache.org/old/publiccorpus/
   Terms: corpus data files released into the public domain / under permissive
   open-data terms by the Apache SpamAssassin project; copyright in individual
   message text remains with the original senders. Messages were collected from
   public fora / public newsletters.

2. **Nazario Phishing Corpus** — used: phishing mbox archives (label = phishing).
   Source: http://monkey.org/~jose/phishing/
   Terms: publicly released research corpus collected by Jose Nazario. No formal
   OSI license is attached; use is academic/research and the corpus must be cited.
   Real phishing URLs in the released benchmark are DEFANGED (see below).

3. **Enron Email Corpus** — used: a sampled subset of legitimate (ham) messages.
   Source: https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~enron/ (CMU release of the FERC dataset).
   Terms: dataset made public during the FERC investigation; widely redistributed
   for research. Contains real names/addresses of Enron personnel as originally
   released; we redistribute only a processed ham subset for classification.

## Derived benchmark (what this project releases)

- The processed, unified dataset and the LLM rewrites are derivative works of the
  above and inherit the most restrictive applicable upstream terms. They are
  released **for non-commercial defensive security research and reproducibility
  only**, consistent with `ETHICS.md`.
- **Defanging:** every URL in the publicly released originals AND rewrites is
  rendered inert (`http://` → `hxxp://`, etc.). No live/clickable phishing links
  are distributed. (Internal feature computation uses verbatim URLs; see README.)
- **No operational uplift:** no payloads, credentials, real targets, or live
  infrastructure are added. Rewrites exist solely as a measurement instrument.

## Citation

If you use PhishRewrite, cite this repository and the three upstream corpora
(SpamAssassin, Nazario, Enron). A `CITATION.cff` / Zenodo DOI will accompany the
released benchmark.

## Removal / takedown

If you are a rights-holder and wish content removed from the derived release,
open an issue and the affected records will be removed.
